7#ifdef USE_MANUAL
8#include "tool_hugehelp.h"
9void hugehelp(void)
10{
11 fputs(
12" _ _ ____ _\n"
13" Project ___| | | | _ \\| |\n"
14" / __| | | | |_) | |\n"
15" | (__| |_| | _ <| |___\n"
16" \\___|\\___/|_| \\_\\_____|\n"
17"\n"
18"NAME\n"
19" curl - transfer a URL\n"
20"\n"
21"SYNOPSIS\n"
22" curl [options] [URL...]\n"
23"\n"
24"DESCRIPTION\n"
25" curl is a tool to transfer data from or to a server, using one of the\n"
26" supported protocols (DICT, FILE, FTP, FTPS, GOPHER, HTTP, HTTPS, IMAP,\n"
27, stdout);
28 fputs(
29" IMAPS, LDAP, LDAPS, POP3, POP3S, RTMP, RTSP, SCP, SFTP, SMB, SMBS,\n"
30" SMTP, SMTPS, TELNET and TFTP). The command is designed to work without\n"
31" user interaction.\n"
32"\n"
33" curl offers a busload of useful tricks like proxy support, user authen-\n"
34" tication, FTP upload, HTTP post, SSL connections, cookies, file trans-\n"
35" fer resume, Metalink, and more. As you will see below, the number of\n"
36" features will make your head spin!\n"
37"\n"
38, stdout);
39 fputs(
40" curl is powered by libcurl for all transfer-related features. See\n"
41" libcurl(3) for details.\n"
42"\n"
43"URL\n"
44" The URL syntax is protocol-dependent. You'll find a detailed descrip-\n"
45" tion in RFC 3986.\n"
46"\n"
47" You can specify multiple URLs or parts of URLs by writing part sets\n"
48" within braces as in:\n"
49"\n"
50" http://site.{one,two,three}.com\n"
51"\n"
52" or you can get sequences of alphanumeric series by using [] as in:\n"
53"\n"
54" ftp://ftp.example.com/file[1-100].txt\n"
55"\n"
56, stdout);
57 fputs(
58" ftp://ftp.example.com/file[001-100].txt (with leading zeros)\n"
59"\n"
60" ftp://ftp.example.com/file[a-z].txt\n"
61"\n"
62" Nested sequences are not supported, but you can use several ones next\n"
63" to each other:\n"
64"\n"
65" http://example.com/archive[1996-1999]/vol[1-4]/part{a,b,c}.html\n"
66"\n"
67" You can specify any amount of URLs on the command line. They will be\n"
68" fetched in a sequential manner in the specified order.\n"
69"\n"
70, stdout);
71 fputs(
72" You can specify a step counter for the ranges to get every Nth number\n"
73" or letter:\n"
74"\n"
75" http://example.com/file[1-100:10].txt\n"
76"\n"
77" http://example.com/file[a-z:2].txt\n"
78"\n"
79" When using [] or {} sequences when invoked from a command line prompt,\n"
80" you probably have to put the full URL within double quotes to avoid the\n"
81" shell from interfering with it. This also goes for other characters\n"
82" treated special, like for example '&', '?' and '*'.\n"
83"\n"
84, stdout);
85 fputs(
86" Provide the IPv6 zone index in the URL with an escaped percentage sign\n"
87" and the interface name. Like in\n"
88"\n"
89" http://[fe80::3%25eth0]/\n"
90"\n"
91" If you specify URL without protocol:// prefix, curl will attempt to\n"
92" guess what protocol you might want. It will then default to HTTP but\n"
93" try other protocols based on often-used host name prefixes. For exam-\n"
94" ple, for host names starting with \"ftp.\" curl will assume you want to\n"
95" speak FTP.\n"
96"\n"
97, stdout);
98 fputs(
99" curl will do its best to use what you pass to it as a URL. It is not\n"
100" trying to validate it as a syntactically correct URL by any means but\n"
101" is instead very liberal with what it accepts.\n"
102"\n"
103" curl will attempt to re-use connections for multiple file transfers, so\n"
104" that getting many files from the same server will not do multiple con-\n"
105" nects / handshakes. This improves speed. Of course this is only done on\n"
106, stdout);
107 fputs(
108" files specified on a single command line and cannot be used between\n"
109" separate curl invokes.\n"
110"\n"
111"PROGRESS METER\n"
112" curl normally displays a progress meter during operations, indicating\n"
113" the amount of transferred data, transfer speeds and estimated time\n"
114" left, etc. The progress meter displays number of bytes and the speeds\n"
115" are in bytes per second. The suffixes (k, M, G, T, P) are 1024 based.\n"
116" For example 1k is 1024 bytes. 1M is 1048576 bytes.\n"
117"\n"
118, stdout);
119 fputs(
120" curl displays this data to the terminal by default, so if you invoke\n"
121" curl to do an operation and it is about to write data to the terminal,\n"
122" it disables the progress meter as otherwise it would mess up the output\n"
123" mixing progress meter and response data.\n"
124"\n"
125" If you want a progress meter for HTTP POST or PUT requests, you need to\n"
126" redirect the response output to a file, using shell redirect (>), -o,\n"
127" --output or similar.\n"
128"\n"
129, stdout);
130 fputs(
131" It is not the same case for FTP upload as that operation does not spit\n"
132" out any response data to the terminal.\n"
133"\n"
134" If you prefer a progress \"bar\" instead of the regular meter, -#,\n"
135" --progress-bar is your friend. You can also disable the progress meter\n"
136" completely with the -s, --silent option.\n"
137"\n"
138"OPTIONS\n"
139" Options start with one or two dashes. Many of the options require an\n"
140" additional value next to them.\n"
141"\n"
142, stdout);
143 fputs(
144" The short \"single-dash\" form of the options, -d for example, may be\n"
145" used with or without a space between it and its value, although a space\n"
146" is a recommended separator. The long \"double-dash\" form, -d, --data for\n"
147" example, requires a space between it and its value.\n"
148"\n"
149" Short version options that don't need any additional values can be used\n"
150" immediately next to each other, like for example you can specify all\n"
151, stdout);
152 fputs(
153" the options -O, -L and -v at once as -OLv.\n"
154"\n"
155" In general, all boolean options are enabled with --option and yet again\n"
156" disabled with --no-option. That is, you use the exact same option name\n"
157" but prefix it with \"no-\". However, in this list we mostly only list and\n"
158" show the --option version of them. (This concept with --no options was\n"
159" added in 7.19.0. Previously most options were toggled on/off on\n"
160" repeated use of the same command line option.)\n"
161, stdout);
162 fputs(
163"\n"
164" --abstract-unix-socket <path>\n"
165" (HTTP) Connect through an abstract Unix domain socket, instead\n"
166" of using the network. Note: netstat shows the path of an\n"
167" abstract socket prefixed with '@', however the <path> argument\n"
168" should not have this leading character.\n"
169"\n"
170" Added in 7.53.0.\n"
171"\n"
172" --anyauth\n"
173" (HTTP) Tells curl to figure out authentication method by itself,\n"
174, stdout);
175 fputs(
176" and use the most secure one the remote site claims to support.\n"
177" This is done by first doing a request and checking the response-\n"
178" headers, thus possibly inducing an extra network round-trip.\n"
179" This is used instead of setting a specific authentication\n"
180" method, which you can do with --basic, --digest, --ntlm, and\n"
181" --negotiate.\n"
182"\n"
183, stdout);
184 fputs(
185" Using --anyauth is not recommended if you do uploads from stdin,\n"
186" since it may require data to be sent twice and then the client\n"
187" must be able to rewind. If the need should arise when uploading\n"
188" from stdin, the upload operation will fail.\n"
189"\n"
190" Used together with -u, --user.\n"
191"\n"
192" See also --proxy-anyauth and --basic and --digest.\n"
193"\n"
194" -a, --append\n"
195, stdout);
196 fputs(
197" (FTP SFTP) When used in an upload, this makes curl append to the\n"
198" target file instead of overwriting it. If the remote file\n"
199" doesn't exist, it will be created. Note that this flag is\n"
200" ignored by some SFTP servers (including OpenSSH).\n"
201"\n"
202" --basic\n"
203" (HTTP) Tells curl to use HTTP Basic authentication with the\n"
204" remote host. This is the default and this option is usually\n"
205, stdout);
206 fputs(
207" pointless, unless you use it to override a previously set option\n"
208" that sets a different authentication method (such as --ntlm,\n"
209" --digest, or --negotiate).\n"
210"\n"
211" Used together with -u, --user.\n"
212"\n"
213" See also --proxy-basic.\n"
214"\n"
215" --cacert <file>\n"
216" (TLS) Tells curl to use the specified certificate file to verify\n"
217" the peer. The file may contain multiple CA certificates. The\n"
218, stdout);
219 fputs(
220" certificate(s) must be in PEM format. Normally curl is built to\n"
221" use a default file for this, so this option is typically used to\n"
222" alter that default file.\n"
223"\n"
224" curl recognizes the environment variable named 'CURL_CA_BUNDLE'\n"
225" if it is set, and uses the given path as a path to a CA cert\n"
226" bundle. This option overrides that variable.\n"
227"\n"
228" The windows version of curl will automatically look for a CA\n"
229, stdout);
230 fputs(
231" certs file named 'curl-ca-bundle.crt', either in the same direc-\n"
232" tory as curl.exe, or in the Current Working Directory, or in any\n"
233" folder along your PATH.\n"
234"\n"
235" If curl is built against the NSS SSL library, the NSS PEM\n"
236" PKCS#11 module (libnsspem.so) needs to be available for this\n"
237" option to work properly.\n"
238"\n"
239" (iOS and macOS only) If curl is built against Secure Transport,\n"
240, stdout);
241 fputs(
242" then this option is supported for backward compatibility with\n"
243" other SSL engines, but it should not be set. If the option is\n"
244" not set, then curl will use the certificates in the system and\n"
245" user Keychain to verify the peer, which is the preferred method\n"
246" of verifying the peer's certificate chain.\n"
247"\n"
248" If this option is used several times, the last one will be used.\n"
249"\n"
250" --capath <dir>\n"
251, stdout);
252 fputs(
253" (TLS) Tells curl to use the specified certificate directory to\n"
254" verify the peer. Multiple paths can be provided by separating\n"
255" them with \":\" (e.g. \"path1:path2:path3\"). The certificates must\n"
256" be in PEM format, and if curl is built against OpenSSL, the\n"
257" directory must have been processed using the c_rehash utility\n"
258" supplied with OpenSSL. Using --capath can allow OpenSSL-powered\n"
259, stdout);
260 fputs(
261" curl to make SSL-connections much more efficiently than using\n"
262" --cacert if the --cacert file contains many CA certificates.\n"
263"\n"
264" If this option is set, the default capath value will be ignored,\n"
265" and if it is used several times, the last one will be used.\n"
266"\n"
267" --cert-status\n"
268" (TLS) Tells curl to verify the status of the server certificate\n"
269" by using the Certificate Status Request (aka. OCSP stapling) TLS\n"
270, stdout);
271 fputs(
272" extension.\n"
273"\n"
274" If this option is enabled and the server sends an invalid (e.g.\n"
275" expired) response, if the response suggests that the server cer-\n"
276" tificate has been revoked, or no response at all is received,\n"
277" the verification fails.\n"
278"\n"
279" This is currently only implemented in the OpenSSL, GnuTLS and\n"
280" NSS backends.\n"
281"\n"
282" Added in 7.41.0.\n"
283"\n"
284" --cert-type <type>\n"
285, stdout);
286 fputs(
287" (TLS) Tells curl what certificate type the provided certificate\n"
288" is in. PEM, DER and ENG are recognized types. If not specified,\n"
289" PEM is assumed.\n"
290"\n"
291" If this option is used several times, the last one will be used.\n"
292"\n"
293" See also -E, --cert and --key and --key-type.\n"
294"\n"
295" -E, --cert <certificate[:password]>\n"
296" (TLS) Tells curl to use the specified client certificate file\n"
297, stdout);
298 fputs(
299" when getting a file with HTTPS, FTPS or another SSL-based proto-\n"
300" col. The certificate must be in PKCS#12 format if using Secure\n"
301" Transport, or PEM format if using any other engine. If the\n"
302" optional password isn't specified, it will be queried for on the\n"
303" terminal. Note that this option assumes a \"certificate\" file\n"
304" that is the private key and the client certificate concatenated!\n"
305, stdout);
306 fputs(
307" See -E, --cert and --key to specify them independently.\n"
308"\n"
309" If curl is built against the NSS SSL library then this option\n"
310" can tell curl the nickname of the certificate to use within the\n"
311" NSS database defined by the environment variable SSL_DIR (or by\n"
312" default /etc/pki/nssdb). If the NSS PEM PKCS#11 module (lib-\n"
313" nsspem.so) is available then PEM files may be loaded. If you\n"
314, stdout);
315 fputs(
316" want to use a file from the current directory, please precede it\n"
317" with \"./\" prefix, in order to avoid confusion with a nickname.\n"
318" If the nickname contains \":\", it needs to be preceded by \"\\\" so\n"
319" that it is not recognized as password delimiter. If the nick-\n"
320" name contains \"\\\", it needs to be escaped as \"\\\\\" so that it is\n"
321" not recognized as an escape character.\n"
322"\n"
323, stdout);
324 fputs(
325" (iOS and macOS only) If curl is built against Secure Transport,\n"
326" then the certificate string can either be the name of a certifi-\n"
327" cate/private key in the system or user keychain, or the path to\n"
328" a PKCS#12-encoded certificate and private key. If you want to\n"
329" use a file from the current directory, please precede it with\n"
330" \"./\" prefix, in order to avoid confusion with a nickname.\n"
331"\n"
332, stdout);
333 fputs(
334" If this option is used several times, the last one will be used.\n"
335"\n"
336" See also --cert-type and --key and --key-type.\n"
337"\n"
338" --ciphers <list of ciphers>\n"
339" (TLS) Specifies which ciphers to use in the connection. The list\n"
340" of ciphers must specify valid ciphers. Read up on SSL cipher\n"
341" list details on this URL:\n"
342"\n"
343" https://curl.haxx.se/docs/ssl-ciphers.html\n"
344"\n"
345, stdout);
346 fputs(
347" If this option is used several times, the last one will be used.\n"
348"\n"
349" --compressed-ssh\n"
350" (SCP SFTP) Enables built-in SSH compression. This is a request,\n"
351" not an order; the server may or may not do it.\n"
352"\n"
353" Added in 7.56.0.\n"
354"\n"
355" --compressed\n"
356" (HTTP) Request a compressed response using one of the algorithms\n"
357" curl supports, and save the uncompressed document. If this\n"
358, stdout);
359 fputs(
360" option is used and the server sends an unsupported encoding,\n"
361" curl will report an error.\n"
362"\n"
363" -K, --config <file>\n"
364"\n"
365" Specify a text file to read curl arguments from. The command\n"
366" line arguments found in the text file will be used as if they\n"
367" were provided on the command line.\n"
368"\n"
369" Options and their parameters must be specified on the same line\n"
370, stdout);
371 fputs(
372" in the file, separated by whitespace, colon, or the equals sign.\n"
373" Long option names can optionally be given in the config file\n"
374" without the initial double dashes and if so, the colon or equals\n"
375" characters can be used as separators. If the option is specified\n"
376" with one or two dashes, there can be no colon or equals charac-\n"
377" ter between the option and its parameter.\n"
378"\n"
379, stdout);
380 fputs(
381" If the parameter is to contain whitespace, the parameter must be\n"
382" enclosed within quotes. Within double quotes, the following\n"
383" escape sequences are available: \\\\, \\\", \\t, \\n, \\r and \\v. A\n"
384" backslash preceding any other letter is ignored. If the first\n"
385" column of a config line is a '#' character, the rest of the line\n"
386" will be treated as a comment. Only write one option per physical\n"
387, stdout);
388 fputs(
389" line in the config file.\n"
390"\n"
391" Specify the filename to -K, --config as '-' to make curl read\n"
392" the file from stdin.\n"
393"\n"
394" Note that to be able to specify a URL in the config file, you\n"
395" need to specify it using the --url option, and not by simply\n"
396" writing the URL on its own line. So, it could look similar to\n"
397" this:\n"
398"\n"
399" url = \"https://curl.haxx.se/docs/\"\n"
400"\n"
401, stdout);
402 fputs(
403" When curl is invoked, it (unless -q, --disable is used) checks\n"
404" for a default config file and uses it if found. The default con-\n"
405" fig file is checked for in the following places in this order:\n"
406"\n"
407" 1) curl tries to find the \"home dir\": It first checks for the\n"
408" CURL_HOME and then the HOME environment variables. Failing that,\n"
409" it uses getpwuid() on Unix-like systems (which returns the home\n"
410, stdout);
411 fputs(
412" dir given the current user in your system). On Windows, it then\n"
413" checks for the APPDATA variable, or as a last resort the '%USER-\n"
414" PROFILE%\\Application Data'.\n"
415"\n"
416" 2) On windows, if there is no _curlrc file in the home dir, it\n"
417" checks for one in the same dir the curl executable is placed. On\n"
418" Unix-like systems, it will simply try to load .curlrc from the\n"
419" determined home dir.\n"
420"\n"
421, stdout);
422 fputs(
423" # --- Example file ---\n"
424" # this is a comment\n"
425" url = \"example.com\"\n"
426" output = \"curlhere.html\"\n"
427" user-agent = \"superagent/1.0\"\n"
428"\n"
429" # and fetch another URL too\n"
430" url = \"example.com/docs/manpage.html\"\n"
431" -O\n"
432" referer = \"http://nowhereatall.example.com/\"\n"
433" # --- End of example file ---\n"
434"\n"
435" This option can be used multiple times to load multiple config\n"
436, stdout);
437 fputs(
438" files.\n"
439"\n"
440" --connect-timeout <seconds>\n"
441" Maximum time in seconds that you allow curl's connection to\n"
442" take. This only limits the connection phase, so if curl con-\n"
443" nects within the given period it will continue - if not it will\n"
444" exit. Since version 7.32.0, this option accepts decimal values.\n"
445" If this option is used several times, the last one will be used.\n"
446"\n"
447" See also -m, --max-time.\n"
448"\n"
449, stdout);
450 fputs(
451" --connect-to <HOST1:PORT1:HOST2:PORT2>\n"
452"\n"
453" For a request to the given HOST1:PORT1 pair, connect to\n"
454" HOST2:PORT2 instead. This option is suitable to direct requests\n"
455" at a specific server, e.g. at a specific cluster node in a clus-\n"
456" ter of servers. This option is only used to establish the net-\n"
457" work connection. It does NOT affect the hostname/port that is\n"
458, stdout);
459 fputs(
460" used for TLS/SSL (e.g. SNI, certificate verification) or for the\n"
461" application protocols. \"HOST1\" and \"PORT1\" may be the empty\n"
462" string, meaning \"any host/port\". \"HOST2\" and \"PORT2\" may also be\n"
463" the empty string, meaning \"use the request's original\n"
464" host/port\".\n"
465"\n"
466" A \"host\" specified to this option is compared as a string, so it\n"
467, stdout);
468 fputs(
469" needs to match the name used in request URL. It can be either\n"
470" numerical such as \"127.0.0.1\" or the full host name such as\n"
471" \"example.org\".\n"
472"\n"
473" This option can be used many times to add many connect rules.\n"
474"\n"
475" See also --resolve and -H, --header. Added in 7.49.0.\n"
476"\n"
477" -C, --continue-at <offset>\n"
478" Continue/Resume a previous file transfer at the given offset.\n"
479, stdout);
480 fputs(
481" The given offset is the exact number of bytes that will be\n"
482" skipped, counting from the beginning of the source file before\n"
483" it is transferred to the destination. If used with uploads, the\n"
484" FTP server command SIZE will not be used by curl.\n"
485"\n"
486" Use \"-C -\" to tell curl to automatically find out where/how to\n"
487" resume the transfer. It then uses the given output/input files\n"
488" to figure that out.\n"
489"\n"
490, stdout);
491 fputs(
492" If this option is used several times, the last one will be used.\n"
493"\n"
494" See also -r, --range.\n"
495"\n"
496" -c, --cookie-jar <filename>\n"
497" (HTTP) Specify to which file you want curl to write all cookies\n"
498" after a completed operation. Curl writes all cookies from its\n"
499" in-memory cookie storage to the given file at the end of opera-\n"
500" tions. If no cookies are known, no data will be written. The\n"
501, stdout);
502 fputs(
503" file will be written using the Netscape cookie file format. If\n"
504" you set the file name to a single dash, \"-\", the cookies will be\n"
505" written to stdout.\n"
506"\n"
507" This command line option will activate the cookie engine that\n"
508" makes curl record and use cookies. Another way to activate it is\n"
509" to use the -b, --cookie option.\n"
510"\n"
511" If the cookie jar can't be created or written to, the whole curl\n"
512, stdout);
513 fputs(
514" operation won't fail or even report an error clearly. Using -v,\n"
515" --verbose will get a warning displayed, but that is the only\n"
516" visible feedback you get about this possibly lethal situation.\n"
517"\n"
518" If this option is used several times, the last specified file\n"
519" name will be used.\n"
520"\n"
521" -b, --cookie <data>\n"
522" (HTTP) Pass the data to the HTTP server in the Cookie header. It\n"
523, stdout);
524 fputs(
525" is supposedly the data previously received from the server in a\n"
526" \"Set-Cookie:\" line. The data should be in the format\n"
527" \"NAME1=VALUE1; NAME2=VALUE2\".\n"
528"\n"
529" If no '=' symbol is used in the argument, it is instead treated\n"
530" as a filename to read previously stored cookie from. This option\n"
531" also activates the cookie engine which will make curl record\n"
532, stdout);
533 fputs(
534" incoming cookies, which may be handy if you're using this in\n"
535" combination with the -L, --location option or do multiple URL\n"
536" transfers on the same invoke.\n"
537"\n"
538" The file format of the file to read cookies from should be plain\n"
539" HTTP headers (Set-Cookie style) or the Netscape/Mozilla cookie\n"
540" file format.\n"
541"\n"
542" The file specified with -b, --cookie is only used as input. No\n"
543, stdout);
544 fputs(
545" cookies will be written to the file. To store cookies, use the\n"
546" -c, --cookie-jar option.\n"
547"\n"
548" Exercise caution if you are using this option and multiple\n"
549" transfers may occur. If you use the NAME1=VALUE1; format, or in\n"
550" a file use the Set-Cookie format and don't specify a domain,\n"
551" then the cookie is sent for any domain (even after redirects are\n"
552, stdout);
553 fputs(
554" followed) and cannot be modified by a server-set cookie. If the\n"
555" cookie engine is enabled and a server sets a cookie of the same\n"
556" name then both will be sent on a future transfer to that server,\n"
557" likely not what you intended. To address these issues set a\n"
558" domain in Set-Cookie (doing that will include sub domains) or\n"
559" use the Netscape format.\n"
560"\n"
561, stdout);
562 fputs(
563" If this option is used several times, the last one will be used.\n"
564" Users very often want to both read cookies from a file and write\n"

869" --fail-early\n"
870" Fail and exit on the first detected transfer error.\n"
871"\n"
872" When curl is used to do multiple transfers on the command line,\n"
873" it will attempt to operate on each given URL, one by one. By\n"
874" default, it will ignore errors if there are more URLs given and\n"
875" the last URL's success will determine the error code curl\n"
876, stdout);
877 fputs(
878" returns. So early failures will be \"hidden\" by subsequent suc-\n"

881" Using this option, curl will instead return an error on the\n"
882" first transfer that fails, independent of the amount of URLs\n"
883" that are given on the command line. This way, no transfer fail-\n"
884" ures go undetected by scripts and similar.\n"

887, stdout);
888 fputs(

890"\n"
891" This option does not imply -f, --fail, which causes transfers to\n"
892" fail due to the server's HTTP status code. You can combine the\n"

894" fore contained by -:, --next.\n"

897"\n"
898" -f, --fail\n"
899" (HTTP) Fail silently (no output at all) on server errors. This\n"
900, stdout);
901 fputs(
902" is mostly done to better enable scripts etc to better deal with\n"

907"\n"

909, stdout);

1111, stdout);

1117" curl does a single CWD operation for each path part in\n"
1118" the given URL. For deep hierarchies this means very many\n"

1120" This is the default but the slowest behavior.\n"

1127"\n"
1128" singlecwd\n"
1129" curl does one CWD with the full target directory and then\n"
1130" operates on the file \"normally\" (like in the multicwd\n"
1131" case). This is somewhat more standards compliant than\n"
1132, stdout);
1133 fputs(
1134" 'nocwd' but without the full penalty of 'multicwd'.\n"
1135"\n"
1136" Added in 7.15.1.\n"
1137"\n"
1138" --ftp-pasv\n"
1139" (FTP) Use passive mode for the data connection. Passive is the\n"
1140" internal default behavior, but using this option can be used to\n"
1141" override a previous -P, --ftp-port option.\n"
1142"\n"
1143" If this option is used several times, only the first one is\n"
1144" used. Undoing an enforced passive really isn't doable but you\n"
1145, stdout);
1146 fputs(
1147" must then instead enforce the correct -P, --ftp-port again.\n"
1148"\n"
1149" Passive mode means that curl will try the EPSV command first and\n"
1150" then PASV, unless --disable-epsv is used.\n"
1151" See also --disable-epsv. Added in 7.11.0.\n"
1152"\n"
1153" -P, --ftp-port <address>\n"
1154" (FTP) Reverses the default initiator/listener roles when con-\n"
1155" necting with FTP. This option makes curl use active mode. curl\n"
1156, stdout);
1157 fputs(
1158" then tells the server to connect back to the client's specified\n"
1159" address and port, while passive mode asks the server to setup an\n"
1160" IP address and port for it to connect to. <address> should be\n"
1161" one of:\n"
1162"\n"
1163" interface\n"
1164" i.e \"eth0\" to specify which interface's IP address you\n"
1165" want to use (Unix only)\n"
1166"\n"
1167" IP address\n"
1168, stdout);
1169 fputs(
1170" i.e \"192.168.10.1\" to specify the exact IP address\n"
1171"\n"
1172" host name\n"
1173" i.e \"my.host.domain\" to specify the machine\n"
1174"\n"
1175" - make curl pick the same IP address that is already used\n"
1176" for the control connection\n"
1177"\n"
1178" If this option is used several times, the last one will be used. Dis-\n"
1179" able the use of PORT with --ftp-pasv. Disable the attempt to use the\n"
1180, stdout);
1181 fputs(
1182" EPRT command instead of PORT by using --disable-eprt. EPRT is really\n"
1183" PORT++.\n"
1184"\n"
1185" Since 7.19.5, you can append \":[start]-[end]\" to the right of the\n"
1186" address, to tell curl what TCP port range to use. That means you spec-\n"
1187" ify a port range, from a lower to a higher number. A single number\n"
1188" works as well, but do note that it increases the risk of failure since\n"
1189" the port may not be available.\n"
1190"\n"
1191" See also --ftp-pasv and --disable-eprt.\n"
1192"\n"
1193, stdout);

1276, stdout);
1277 fputs(

1280" that if you should add a custom header that has the same name as\n"

1299"\n"
1300" Starting in 7.55.0, this option can take an argument in @file-\n"

1303 fputs(

1310"\n"

1315" WARNING: headers set with this option will be set in all\n"
1316, stdout);
1317 fputs(

2783, stdout);

4084"USING PASSWORDS\n"
4085"\n"
4086" FTP\n"
4087"\n"
4088" To ftp files using name+passwd, include them in the URL like:\n"
4089"\n"
4090" curl ftp://name:passwd@machine.domain:port/full/path/to/file\n"
4091"\n"
4092" or specify them with the -u flag like\n"
4093"\n"
4094" curl -u name:passwd ftp://machine.domain:port/full/path/to/file\n"
4095"\n"
4096" FTPS\n"
4097"\n"
4098, stdout);
4099 fputs(
4100" It is just like for FTP, but you may also want to specify and use\n"
4101" SSL-specific options for certificates etc.\n"
4102"\n"
4103" Note that using FTPS:// as prefix is the \"implicit\" way as described in the\n"
4104" standards while the recommended \"explicit\" way is done by using FTP:// and\n"
4105" the --ftp-ssl option.\n"
4106"\n"
4107" SFTP / SCP\n"
4108"\n"
4109" This is similar to FTP, but you can use the --key option to specify a\n"
4110" private key to use instead of a password. Note that the private key may\n"
4111, stdout);
4112 fputs(
4113" itself be protected by a password that is unrelated to the login password\n"
4114" of the remote system; this password is specified using the --pass option.\n"
4115" Typically, curl will automatically extract the public key from the private\n"
4116" key file, but in cases where curl does not have the proper library support,\n"
4117" a matching public key file must be specified using the --pubkey option.\n"
4118"\n"
4119" HTTP\n"
4120"\n"
4121" Curl also supports user and password in HTTP URLs, thus you can pick a file\n"
4122" like:\n"
4123"\n"
4124, stdout);
4125 fputs(
4126" curl http://name:passwd@machine.domain/full/path/to/file\n"
4127"\n"
4128" or specify user and password separately like in\n"
4129"\n"
4130" curl -u name:passwd http://machine.domain/full/path/to/file\n"
4131"\n"
4132" HTTP offers many different methods of authentication and curl supports\n"
4133" several: Basic, Digest, NTLM and Negotiate (SPNEGO). Without telling which\n"
4134" method to use, curl defaults to Basic. You can also ask curl to pick the\n"
4135" most secure ones out of the ones that the server accepts for the given URL,\n"
4136, stdout);
4137 fputs(
4138" by using --anyauth.\n"
4139"\n"
4140" NOTE! According to the URL specification, HTTP URLs can not contain a user\n"
4141" and password, so that style will not work when using curl via a proxy, even\n"
4142" though curl allows it at other times. When using a proxy, you _must_ use\n"
4143" the -u style for user and password.\n"
4144"\n"
4145" HTTPS\n"
4146"\n"
4147" Probably most commonly used with private certificates, as explained below.\n"
4148"\n"
4149"PROXY\n"
4150"\n"
4151" curl supports both HTTP and SOCKS proxy servers, with optional authentication.\n"
4152, stdout);
4153 fputs(
4154" It does not have special support for FTP proxy servers since there are no\n"
4155" standards for those, but it can still be made to work with many of them. You\n"
4156" can also use both HTTP and SOCKS proxies to transfer files to and from FTP\n"
4157" servers.\n"
4158"\n"
4159" Get an ftp file using an HTTP proxy named my-proxy that uses port 888:\n"
4160"\n"
4161" curl -x my-proxy:888 ftp://ftp.leachsite.com/README\n"
4162"\n"
4163" Get a file from an HTTP server that requires user and password, using the\n"
4164" same proxy as above:\n"
4165"\n"
4166, stdout);
4167 fputs(
4168" curl -u user:passwd -x my-proxy:888 http://www.get.this/\n"
4169"\n"
4170" Some proxies require special authentication. Specify by using -U as above:\n"
4171"\n"
4172" curl -U user:passwd -x my-proxy:888 http://www.get.this/\n"
4173"\n"
4174" A comma-separated list of hosts and domains which do not use the proxy can\n"
4175" be specified as:\n"
4176"\n"
4177" curl --noproxy localhost,get.this -x my-proxy:888 http://www.get.this/\n"
4178"\n"
4179" If the proxy is specified with --proxy1.0 instead of --proxy or -x, then\n"
4180, stdout);
4181 fputs(
4182" curl will use HTTP/1.0 instead of HTTP/1.1 for any CONNECT attempts.\n"
4183"\n"
4184" curl also supports SOCKS4 and SOCKS5 proxies with --socks4 and --socks5.\n"
4185"\n"
4186" See also the environment variables Curl supports that offer further proxy\n"
4187" control.\n"
4188"\n"
4189" Most FTP proxy servers are set up to appear as a normal FTP server from the\n"
4190" client's perspective, with special commands to select the remote FTP server.\n"
4191" curl supports the -u, -Q and --ftp-account options that can be used to\n"
4192, stdout);
4193 fputs(
4194" set up transfers through many FTP proxies. For example, a file can be\n"
4195" uploaded to a remote FTP server using a Blue Coat FTP proxy with the\n"
4196" options:\n"
4197"\n"
4198" curl -u \"Remote-FTP-Username@remote.ftp.server Proxy-Username:Remote-Pass\" \\\n"
4199" --ftp-account Proxy-Password --upload-file local-file \\\n"
4200" ftp://my-ftp.proxy.server:21/remote/upload/path/\n"
4201"\n"
4202" See the manual for your FTP proxy to determine the form it expects to set up\n"
4203" transfers, and curl's -v option to see exactly what curl is sending.\n"
4204"\n"
4205, stdout);
4206 fputs(
4207"RANGES\n"
4208"\n"
4209" HTTP 1.1 introduced byte-ranges. Using this, a client can request\n"
4210" to get only one or more subparts of a specified document. Curl supports\n"
4211" this with the -r flag.\n"
4212"\n"
4213" Get the first 100 bytes of a document:\n"
4214"\n"
4215" curl -r 0-99 http://www.get.this/\n"
4216"\n"
4217" Get the last 500 bytes of a document:\n"
4218"\n"
4219" curl -r -500 http://www.get.this/\n"
4220"\n"
4221" Curl also supports simple ranges for FTP files as well. Then you can only\n"
4222" specify start and stop position.\n"
4223"\n"
4224, stdout);
4225 fputs(
4226" Get the first 100 bytes of a document using FTP:\n"
4227"\n"
4228" curl -r 0-99 ftp://www.get.this/README\n"
4229"\n"
4230"UPLOADING\n"
4231"\n"
4232" FTP / FTPS / SFTP / SCP\n"

4235"\n"

4237"\n"
4238" Upload data from a specified file, login with user and password:\n"

4253" Curl also supports ftp upload through a proxy, but only if the proxy is\n"

4256"\n"
4257" curl --proxytunnel -x proxy:port -T localfile ftp.upload.com\n"
4258"\n"

4296"DETAILED INFORMATION\n"
4297"\n"
4298, stdout);
4299 fputs(
4300" Different protocols provide different ways of getting detailed information\n"
4301" about specific files/documents. To get curl to show detailed information\n"
4302" about a single file, you should use -I/--head option. It displays all\n"
4303" available info on a single file for HTTP and FTP. The HTTP information is a\n"
4304" lot more extensive.\n"
4305"\n"
4306" For HTTP, you can get the header information (the same as -I would show)\n"
4307" shown before the data by using -i/--include. Curl understands the\n"
4308, stdout);
4309 fputs(
4310" -D/--dump-header option when getting files from both FTP and HTTP, and it\n"
4311" will then store the headers in the specified file.\n"
4312"\n"
4313" Store the HTTP headers in a separate file (headers.txt in the example):\n"
4314"\n"

4316"\n"
4317" Note that headers stored in a separate file can be very useful at a later\n"

4320"\n"
4321"POST (HTTP)\n"
4322"\n"
4323, stdout);
4324 fputs(
4325" It's easy to post data using curl. This is done using the -d <data>\n"
4326" option. The post data must be urlencoded.\n"
4327"\n"
4328" Post a simple \"name\" and \"phone\" guestbook.\n"
4329"\n"
4330" curl -d \"name=Rafael%20Sagula&phone=3320780\" \\\n"
4331" http://www.where.com/guest.cgi\n"
4332"\n"
4333" How to post a form with curl, lesson #1:\n"
4334"\n"
4335" Dig out all the <input> tags in the form that you want to fill in. (There's\n"
4336" a perl program called formfind.pl on the curl site that helps with this).\n"
4337"\n"
4338, stdout);
4339 fputs(
4340" If there's a \"normal\" post, you use -d to post. -d takes a full \"post\n"
4341" string\", which is in the format\n"
4342"\n"
4343" <variable1>=<data1>&<variable2>=<data2>&...\n"
4344"\n"
4345" The 'variable' names are the names set with \"name=\" in the <input> tags, and\n"
4346" the data is the contents you want to fill in for the inputs. The data *must*\n"
4347" be properly URL encoded. That means you replace space with + and that you\n"
4348" replace weird letters with %XX where XX is the hexadecimal representation of\n"
4349, stdout);
4350 fputs(
4351" the letter's ASCII code.\n"
4352"\n"
4353" Example:\n"
4354"\n"
4355" (page located at http://www.formpost.com/getthis/\n"
4356"\n"
4357" <form action=\"post.cgi\" method=\"post\">\n"
4358" <input name=user size=10>\n"
4359" <input name=pass type=password size=10>\n"
4360" <input name=id type=hidden value=\"blablabla\">\n"
4361" <input name=ding value=\"submit\">\n"
4362" </form>\n"
4363"\n"
4364" We want to enter user 'foobar' with password '12345'.\n"
4365"\n"
4366" To post to this, you enter a curl command line like:\n"
4367"\n"
4368, stdout);
4369 fputs(
4370" curl -d \"user=foobar&pass=12345&id=blablabla&ding=submit\" (continues)\n"
4371" http://www.formpost.com/getthis/post.cgi\n"
4372"\n"
4373"\n"
4374" While -d uses the application/x-www-form-urlencoded mime-type, generally\n"
4375" understood by CGI's and similar, curl also supports the more capable\n"
4376" multipart/form-data type. This latter type supports things like file upload.\n"
4377"\n"
4378" -F accepts parameters like -F \"name=contents\". If you want the contents to\n"
4379, stdout);
4380 fputs(
4381" be read from a file, use <@filename> as contents. When specifying a file,\n"
4382" you can also specify the file content type by appending ';type=<mime type>'\n"
4383" to the file name. You can also post the contents of several files in one\n"
4384" field. For example, the field name 'coolfiles' is used to send three files,\n"
4385" with different content types using the following syntax:\n"
4386"\n"
4387" curl -F \"coolfiles=@fil1.gif;type=image/gif,fil2.txt,fil3.html\" \\\n"
4388" http://www.post.com/postit.cgi\n"
4389"\n"
4390, stdout);
4391 fputs(
4392" If the content-type is not specified, curl will try to guess from the file\n"
4393" extension (it only knows a few), or use the previously specified type (from\n"
4394" an earlier file if several files are specified in a list) or else it will\n"
4395" use the default type 'application/octet-stream'.\n"
4396"\n"
4397" Emulate a fill-in form with -F. Let's say you fill in three fields in a\n"
4398" form. One field is a file name which to post, one field is your name and one\n"
4399, stdout);
4400 fputs(
4401" field is a file description. We want to post the file we have written named\n"
4402" \"cooltext.txt\". To let curl do the posting of this data instead of your\n"
4403" favourite browser, you have to read the HTML source of the form page and\n"
4404" find the names of the input fields. In our example, the input field names\n"
4405" are 'file', 'yourname' and 'filedescription'.\n"
4406"\n"
4407" curl -F \"file=@cooltext.txt\" -F \"yourname=Daniel\" \\\n"
4408" -F \"filedescription=Cool text file with cool text inside\" \\\n"
4409, stdout);
4410 fputs(
4411" http://www.post.com/postit.cgi\n"
4412"\n"
4413" To send two files in one post you can do it in two ways:\n"
4414"\n"
4415" 1. Send multiple files in a single \"field\" with a single field name:\n"
4416"\n"
4417" curl -F \"pictures=@dog.gif,cat.gif\"\n"
4418"\n"
4419" 2. Send two fields with two field names:\n"
4420"\n"
4421" curl -F \"docpicture=@dog.gif\" -F \"catpicture=@cat.gif\"\n"
4422"\n"
4423" To send a field value literally without interpreting a leading '@'\n"
4424" or '<', or an embedded ';type=', use --form-string instead of\n"
4425, stdout);
4426 fputs(
4427" -F. This is recommended when the value is obtained from a user or\n"
4428" some other unpredictable source. Under these circumstances, using\n"
4429" -F instead of --form-string would allow a user to trick curl into\n"
4430" uploading a file.\n"
4431"\n"
4432"REFERRER\n"
4433"\n"
4434" An HTTP request has the option to include information about which address\n"
4435" referred it to the actual page. Curl allows you to specify the\n"
4436" referrer to be used on the command line. It is especially useful to\n"
4437, stdout);
4438 fputs(
4439" fool or trick stupid servers or CGI scripts that rely on that information\n"
4440" being available or contain certain data.\n"
4441"\n"
4442" curl -e www.coolsite.com http://www.showme.com/\n"
4443"\n"
4444" NOTE: The Referer: [sic] field is defined in the HTTP spec to be a full URL.\n"
4445"\n"
4446"USER AGENT\n"
4447"\n"
4448" An HTTP request has the option to include information about the browser\n"
4449" that generated the request. Curl allows it to be specified on the command\n"
4450" line. It is especially useful to fool or trick stupid servers or CGI\n"
4451, stdout);
4452 fputs(
4453" scripts that only accept certain browsers.\n"
4454"\n"
4455" Example:\n"
4456"\n"
4457" curl -A 'Mozilla/3.0 (Win95; I)' http://www.nationsbank.com/\n"
4458"\n"
4459" Other common strings:\n"
4460" 'Mozilla/3.0 (Win95; I)' Netscape Version 3 for Windows 95\n"
4461" 'Mozilla/3.04 (Win95; U)' Netscape Version 3 for Windows 95\n"
4462" 'Mozilla/2.02 (OS/2; U)' Netscape Version 2 for OS/2\n"
4463" 'Mozilla/4.04 [en] (X11; U; AIX 4.2; Nav)' NS for AIX\n"
4464" 'Mozilla/4.05 [en] (X11; U; Linux 2.0.32 i586)' NS for Linux\n"
4465"\n"
4466, stdout);
4467 fputs(
4468" Note that Internet Explorer tries hard to be compatible in every way:\n"
4469" 'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 4.01; Windows 95)' MSIE for W95\n"
4470"\n"
4471" Mozilla is not the only possible User-Agent name:\n"
4472" 'Konqueror/1.0' KDE File Manager desktop client\n"
4473" 'Lynx/2.7.1 libwww-FM/2.14' Lynx command line browser\n"
4474"\n"
4475"COOKIES\n"
4476"\n"
4477" Cookies are generally used by web servers to keep state information at the\n"
4478" client's side. The server sets cookies by sending a response line in the\n"
4479, stdout);
4480 fputs(
4481" headers that looks like 'Set-Cookie: <data>' where the data part then\n"
4482" typically contains a set of NAME=VALUE pairs (separated by semicolons ';'\n"
4483" like \"NAME1=VALUE1; NAME2=VALUE2;\"). The server can also specify for what\n"
4484" path the \"cookie\" should be used for (by specifying \"path=value\"), when the\n"
4485" cookie should expire (\"expire=DATE\"), for what domain to use it\n"
4486" (\"domain=NAME\") and if it should be used on secure connections only\n"
4487" (\"secure\").\n"
4488"\n"
4489, stdout);
4490 fputs(
4491" If you've received a page from a server that contains a header like:\n"
4492" Set-Cookie: sessionid=boo123; path=\"/foo\";\n"
4493"\n"
4494" it means the server wants that first pair passed on when we get anything in\n"
4495" a path beginning with \"/foo\".\n"
4496"\n"
4497" Example, get a page that wants my name passed in a cookie:\n"
4498"\n"
4499" curl -b \"name=Daniel\" www.sillypage.com\n"
4500"\n"
4501" Curl also has the ability to use previously received cookies in following\n"
4502" sessions. If you get cookies from a server and store them in a file in a\n"
4503, stdout);
4504 fputs(
4505" manner similar to:\n"
4506"\n"
4507" curl --dump-header headers www.example.com\n"
4508"\n"
4509" ... you can then in a second connect to that (or another) site, use the\n"
4510" cookies from the 'headers' file like:\n"
4511"\n"
4512" curl -b headers www.example.com\n"
4513"\n"
4514" While saving headers to a file is a working way to store cookies, it is\n"
4515" however error-prone and not the preferred way to do this. Instead, make curl\n"
4516" save the incoming cookies using the well-known netscape cookie format like\n"
4517" this:\n"
4518"\n"
4519, stdout);
4520 fputs(
4521" curl -c cookies.txt www.example.com\n"
4522"\n"
4523" Note that by specifying -b you enable the \"cookie awareness\" and with -L\n"
4524" you can make curl follow a location: (which often is used in combination\n"
4525" with cookies). So that if a site sends cookies and a location, you can\n"
4526" use a non-existing file to trigger the cookie awareness like:\n"
4527"\n"
4528" curl -L -b empty.txt www.example.com\n"
4529"\n"
4530" The file to read cookies from must be formatted using plain HTTP headers OR\n"
4531, stdout);
4532 fputs(
4533" as netscape's cookie file. Curl will determine what kind it is based on the\n"
4534" file contents. In the above command, curl will parse the header and store\n"
4535" the cookies received from www.example.com. curl will send to the server the\n"
4536" stored cookies which match the request as it follows the location. The\n"
4537" file \"empty.txt\" may be a nonexistent file.\n"
4538"\n"
4539" To read and write cookies from a netscape cookie file, you can set both -b\n"
4540" and -c to use the same file:\n"
4541"\n"
4542, stdout);
4543 fputs(
4544" curl -b cookies.txt -c cookies.txt www.example.com\n"
4545"\n"
4546"PROGRESS METER\n"
4547"\n"
4548" The progress meter exists to show a user that something actually is\n"
4549" happening. The different fields in the output have the following meaning:\n"
4550"\n"
4551" % Total % Received % Xferd Average Speed Time Curr.\n"
4552" Dload Upload Total Current Left Speed\n"
4553" 0 151M 0 38608 0 0 9406 0 4:41:43 0:00:04 4:41:39 9287\n"
4554"\n"
4555" From left-to-right:\n"
4556, stdout);
4557 fputs(
4558" % - percentage completed of the whole transfer\n"
4559" Total - total size of the whole expected transfer\n"
4560" % - percentage completed of the download\n"
4561" Received - currently downloaded amount of bytes\n"
4562" % - percentage completed of the upload\n"
4563" Xferd - currently uploaded amount of bytes\n"
4564" Average Speed\n"
4565" Dload - the average transfer speed of the download\n"
4566" Average Speed\n"
4567" Upload - the average transfer speed of the upload\n"
4568, stdout);
4569 fputs(
4570" Time Total - expected time to complete the operation\n"
4571" Time Current - time passed since the invoke\n"
4572" Time Left - expected time left to completion\n"
4573" Curr.Speed - the average transfer speed the last 5 seconds (the first\n"
4574" 5 seconds of a transfer is based on less time of course.)\n"
4575"\n"
4576" The -# option will display a totally different progress bar that doesn't\n"
4577" need much explanation!\n"
4578"\n"
4579"SPEED LIMIT\n"
4580"\n"
4581, stdout);
4582 fputs(
4583" Curl allows the user to set the transfer speed conditions that must be met\n"
4584" to let the transfer keep going. By using the switch -y and -Y you\n"
4585" can make curl abort transfers if the transfer speed is below the specified\n"
4586" lowest limit for a specified time.\n"
4587"\n"
4588" To have curl abort the download if the speed is slower than 3000 bytes per\n"
4589" second for 1 minute, run:\n"
4590"\n"
4591" curl -Y 3000 -y 60 www.far-away-site.com\n"
4592"\n"
4593" This can very well be used in combination with the overall time limit, so\n"
4594, stdout);
4595 fputs(
4596" that the above operation must be completed in whole within 30 minutes:\n"
4597"\n"
4598" curl -m 1800 -Y 3000 -y 60 www.far-away-site.com\n"
4599"\n"
4600" Forcing curl not to transfer data faster than a given rate is also possible,\n"
4601" which might be useful if you're using a limited bandwidth connection and you\n"
4602" don't want your transfer to use all of it (sometimes referred to as\n"
4603" \"bandwidth throttle\").\n"
4604"\n"
4605" Make curl transfer data no faster than 10 kilobytes per second:\n"
4606"\n"
4607, stdout);
4608 fputs(
4609" curl --limit-rate 10K www.far-away-site.com\n"
4610"\n"
4611" or\n"
4612"\n"
4613" curl --limit-rate 10240 www.far-away-site.com\n"
4614"\n"
4615" Or prevent curl from uploading data faster than 1 megabyte per second:\n"
4616"\n"
4617" curl -T upload --limit-rate 1M ftp://uploadshereplease.com\n"
4618"\n"
4619" When using the --limit-rate option, the transfer rate is regulated on a\n"
4620" per-second basis, which will cause the total transfer speed to become lower\n"
4621" than the given number. Sometimes of course substantially lower, if your\n"
4622, stdout);
4623 fputs(
4624" transfer stalls during periods.\n"
4625"\n"
4626"CONFIG FILE\n"
4627"\n"
4628" Curl automatically tries to read the .curlrc file (or _curlrc file on win32\n"
4629" systems) from the user's home dir on startup.\n"
4630"\n"
4631" The config file could be made up with normal command line switches, but you\n"
4632" can also specify the long options without the dashes to make it more\n"
4633" readable. You can separate the options and the parameter with spaces, or\n"
4634" with = or :. Comments can be used within the file. If the first letter on a\n"
4635, stdout);
4636 fputs(
4637" line is a '#'-symbol the rest of the line is treated as a comment.\n"
4638"\n"
4639" If you want the parameter to contain spaces, you must enclose the entire\n"
4640" parameter within double quotes (\"). Within those quotes, you specify a\n"
4641" quote as \\\".\n"
4642"\n"
4643" NOTE: You must specify options and their arguments on the same line.\n"
4644"\n"
4645" Example, set default time out and proxy in a config file:\n"
4646"\n"
4647" # We want a 30 minute timeout:\n"
4648" -m 1800\n"
4649" # ... and we use a proxy for all accesses:\n"
4650, stdout);
4651 fputs(
4652" proxy = proxy.our.domain.com:8080\n"
4653"\n"
4654" White spaces ARE significant at the end of lines, but all white spaces\n"
4655" leading up to the first characters of each line are ignored.\n"
4656"\n"
4657" Prevent curl from reading the default file by using -q as the first command\n"
4658" line parameter, like:\n"
4659"\n"
4660" curl -q www.thatsite.com\n"
4661"\n"
4662" Force curl to get and display a local help page in case it is invoked\n"
4663" without URL by making a config file similar to:\n"
4664"\n"
4665" # default url to get\n"
4666, stdout);
4667 fputs(
4668" url = \"http://help.with.curl.com/curlhelp.html\"\n"
4669"\n"
4670" You can specify another config file to be read by using the -K/--config\n"
4671" flag. If you set config file name to \"-\" it'll read the config from stdin,\n"
4672" which can be handy if you want to hide options from being visible in process\n"
4673" tables etc:\n"
4674"\n"
4675" echo \"user = user:passwd\" | curl -K - http://that.secret.site.com\n"
4676"\n"
4677"EXTRA HEADERS\n"
4678"\n"
4679" When using curl in your own very special programs, you may end up needing\n"
4680, stdout);
4681 fputs(
4682" to pass on your own custom headers when getting a web page. You can do\n"
4683" this by using the -H flag.\n"
4684"\n"
4685" Example, send the header \"X-you-and-me: yes\" to the server when getting a\n"
4686" page:\n"
4687"\n"
4688" curl -H \"X-you-and-me: yes\" www.love.com\n"
4689"\n"
4690" This can also be useful in case you want curl to send a different text in a\n"
4691" header than it normally does. The -H header you specify then replaces the\n"
4692" header curl would normally send. If you replace an internal header with an\n"
4693, stdout);
4694 fputs(
4695" empty one, you prevent that header from being sent. To prevent the Host:\n"
4696" header from being used:\n"
4697"\n"
4698" curl -H \"Host:\" www.server.com\n"
4699"\n"
4700"FTP and PATH NAMES\n"
4701"\n"
4702" Do note that when getting files with the ftp:// URL, the given path is\n"
4703" relative the directory you enter. To get the file 'README' from your home\n"
4704" directory at your ftp site, do:\n"
4705"\n"
4706" curl ftp://user:passwd@my.site.com/README\n"
4707"\n"
4708" But if you want the README file from the root directory of that very same\n"
4709, stdout);
4710 fputs(
4711" site, you need to specify the absolute file name:\n"
4712"\n"
4713" curl ftp://user:passwd@my.site.com//README\n"
4714"\n"
4715" (I.e with an extra slash in front of the file name.)\n"
4716"\n"
4717"SFTP and SCP and PATH NAMES\n"
4718"\n"
4719" With sftp: and scp: URLs, the path name given is the absolute name on the\n"
4720" server. To access a file relative to the remote user's home directory,\n"
4721" prefix the file with /~/ , such as:\n"
4722"\n"
4723" curl -u $USER sftp://home.example.com/~/.bashrc\n"
4724"\n"
4725"FTP and firewalls\n"
4726"\n"
4727, stdout);
4728 fputs(
4729" The FTP protocol requires one of the involved parties to open a second\n"
4730" connection as soon as data is about to get transferred. There are two ways to\n"
4731" do this.\n"
4732"\n"
4733" The default way for curl is to issue the PASV command which causes the\n"
4734" server to open another port and await another connection performed by the\n"
4735" client. This is good if the client is behind a firewall that doesn't allow\n"
4736" incoming connections.\n"
4737"\n"
4738" curl ftp.download.com\n"
4739"\n"
4740, stdout);
4741 fputs(
4742" If the server, for example, is behind a firewall that doesn't allow connections\n"
4743" on ports other than 21 (or if it just doesn't support the PASV command), the\n"
4744" other way to do it is to use the PORT command and instruct the server to\n"
4745" connect to the client on the given IP number and port (as parameters to the\n"
4746" PORT command).\n"
4747"\n"
4748" The -P flag to curl supports a few different options. Your machine may have\n"
4749" several IP-addresses and/or network interfaces and curl allows you to select\n"
4750, stdout);
4751 fputs(
4752" which of them to use. Default address can also be used:\n"
4753"\n"
4754" curl -P - ftp.download.com\n"
4755"\n"
4756" Download with PORT but use the IP address of our 'le0' interface (this does\n"
4757" not work on windows):\n"
4758"\n"
4759" curl -P le0 ftp.download.com\n"
4760"\n"
4761" Download with PORT but use 192.168.0.10 as our IP address to use:\n"
4762"\n"
4763" curl -P 192.168.0.10 ftp.download.com\n"
4764"\n"
4765"NETWORK INTERFACE\n"
4766"\n"
4767" Get a web page from a server using a specified port for the interface:\n"
4768"\n"
4769, stdout);
4770 fputs(
4771" curl --interface eth0:1 http://www.netscape.com/\n"
4772"\n"
4773" or\n"
4774"\n"
4775" curl --interface 192.168.1.10 http://www.netscape.com/\n"
4776"\n"
4777"HTTPS\n"
4778"\n"
4779" Secure HTTP requires SSL libraries to be installed and used when curl is\n"
4780" built. If that is done, curl is capable of retrieving and posting documents\n"
4781" using the HTTPS protocol.\n"
4782"\n"
4783" Example:\n"
4784"\n"
4785" curl https://www.secure-site.com\n"
4786"\n"
4787" Curl is also capable of using your personal certificates to get/post files\n"
4788, stdout);
4789 fputs(
4790" from sites that require valid certificates. The only drawback is that the\n"
4791" certificate needs to be in PEM-format. PEM is a standard and open format to\n"
4792" store certificates with, but it is not used by the most commonly used\n"
4793" browsers (Netscape and MSIE both use the so called PKCS#12 format). If you\n"
4794" want curl to use the certificates you use with your (favourite) browser, you\n"
4795" may need to download/compile a converter that can convert your browser's\n"
4796, stdout);
4797 fputs(
4798" formatted certificates to PEM formatted ones. This kind of converter is\n"
4799" included in recent versions of OpenSSL, and for older versions Dr Stephen\n"
4800" N. Henson has written a patch for SSLeay that adds this functionality. You\n"
4801" can get his patch (that requires an SSLeay installation) from his site at:\n"
4802" http://www.drh-consultancy.demon.co.uk/\n"
4803"\n"
4804" Example on how to automatically retrieve a document using a certificate with\n"
4805" a personal password:\n"
4806"\n"
4807, stdout);
4808 fputs(
4809" curl -E /path/to/cert.pem:password https://secure.site.com/\n"
4810"\n"
4811" If you neglect to specify the password on the command line, you will be\n"
4812" prompted for the correct password before any data can be received.\n"
4813"\n"
4814" Many older SSL-servers have problems with SSLv3 or TLS, which newer versions\n"
4815" of OpenSSL etc use, therefore it is sometimes useful to specify what\n"
4816" SSL-version curl should use. Use -3, -2 or -1 to specify that exact SSL\n"
4817" version to use (for SSLv3, SSLv2 or TLSv1 respectively):\n"
4818"\n"
4819, stdout);
4820 fputs(
4821" curl -2 https://secure.site.com/\n"
4822"\n"
4823" Otherwise, curl will first attempt to use v3 and then v2.\n"
4824"\n"
4825" To use OpenSSL to convert your favourite browser's certificate into a PEM\n"
4826" formatted one that curl can use, do something like this:\n"
4827"\n"
4828" In Netscape, you start with hitting the 'Security' menu button.\n"
4829"\n"
4830" Select 'certificates->yours' and then pick a certificate in the list\n"
4831"\n"
4832" Press the 'Export' button\n"
4833"\n"
4834" enter your PIN code for the certs\n"
4835"\n"
4836" select a proper place to save it\n"
4837"\n"
4838, stdout);
4839 fputs(
4840" Run the 'openssl' application to convert the certificate. If you cd to the\n"
4841" openssl installation, you can do it like:\n"
4842"\n"
4843" # ./apps/openssl pkcs12 -in [file you saved] -clcerts -out [PEMfile]\n"
4844"\n"
4845" In Firefox, select Options, then Advanced, then the Encryption tab,\n"
4846" View Certificates. This opens the Certificate Manager, where you can\n"
4847" Export. Be sure to select PEM for the Save as type.\n"
4848"\n"
4849" In Internet Explorer, select Internet Options, then the Content tab, then\n"
4850, stdout);
4851 fputs(
4852" Certificates. Then you can Export, and depending on the format you may\n"
4853" need to convert to PEM.\n"
4854"\n"
4855" In Chrome, select Settings, then Show Advanced Settings. Under HTTPS/SSL\n"
4856" select Manage Certificates.\n"
4857"\n"
4858"RESUMING FILE TRANSFERS\n"
4859"\n"
4860" To continue a file transfer where it was previously aborted, curl supports\n"
4861" resume on HTTP(S) downloads as well as FTP uploads and downloads.\n"
4862"\n"
4863" Continue downloading a document:\n"
4864"\n"
4865" curl -C - -o file ftp://ftp.server.com/path/file\n"
4866"\n"
4867, stdout);
4868 fputs(
4869" Continue uploading a document(*1):\n"
4870"\n"
4871" curl -C - -T file ftp://ftp.server.com/path/file\n"
4872"\n"
4873" Continue downloading a document from a web server(*2):\n"
4874"\n"
4875" curl -C - -o file http://www.server.com/\n"
4876"\n"
4877" (*1) = This requires that the FTP server supports the non-standard command\n"
4878" SIZE. If it doesn't, curl will say so.\n"
4879"\n"
4880" (*2) = This requires that the web server supports at least HTTP/1.1. If it\n"
4881" doesn't, curl will say so.\n"
4882"\n"
4883"TIME CONDITIONS\n"
4884"\n"
4885, stdout);
4886 fputs(
4887" HTTP allows a client to specify a time condition for the document it\n"
4888" requests. It is If-Modified-Since or If-Unmodified-Since. Curl allows you to\n"
4889" specify them with the -z/--time-cond flag.\n"
4890"\n"
4891" For example, you can easily make a download that only gets performed if the\n"
4892" remote file is newer than a local copy. It would be made like:\n"
4893"\n"
4894" curl -z local.html http://remote.server.com/remote.html\n"
4895"\n"
4896" Or you can download a file only if the local file is newer than the remote\n"
4897, stdout);
4898 fputs(
4899" one. Do this by prepending the date string with a '-', as in:\n"
4900"\n"
4901" curl -z -local.html http://remote.server.com/remote.html\n"
4902"\n"
4903" You can specify a \"free text\" date as condition. Tell curl to only download\n"
4904" the file if it was updated since January 12, 2012:\n"
4905"\n"
4906" curl -z \"Jan 12 2012\" http://remote.server.com/remote.html\n"
4907"\n"
4908" Curl will then accept a wide range of date formats. You always make the date\n"
4909" check the other way around by prepending it with a dash '-'.\n"
4910"\n"
4911"DICT\n"
4912"\n"
4913" For fun try\n"
4914"\n"
4915, stdout);
4916 fputs(
4917" curl dict://dict.org/m:curl\n"
4918" curl dict://dict.org/d:heisenbug:jargon\n"

4930" curl dict://dict.org/show:strat\n"

4933 fputs(

4935"\n"
4936"LDAP\n"
4937"\n"
4938" If you have installed the OpenLDAP library, curl can take advantage of it\n"
4939" and offer ldap:// support.\n"
4940" On Windows, curl will use WinLDAP from Platform SDK by default.\n"
4941"\n"
4942" Default protocol version used by curl is LDAPv3. LDAPv2 will be used as\n"
4943" fallback mechanism in case if LDAPv3 will fail to connect.\n"
4944"\n"
4945" LDAP is a complex thing and writing an LDAP query is not an easy task. I do\n"
4946, stdout);
4947 fputs(
4948" advise you to dig up the syntax description for that elsewhere. One such\n"
4949" place might be:\n"
4950"\n"
4951" RFC 2255, \"The LDAP URL Format\" https://curl.haxx.se/rfc/rfc2255.txt\n"
4952"\n"
4953" To show you an example, this is how I can get all people from my local LDAP\n"
4954" server that has a certain sub-domain in their email address:\n"
4955"\n"
4956" curl -B \"ldap://ldap.frontec.se/o=frontec??sub?mail=*sth.frontec.se\"\n"
4957"\n"
4958" If I want the same info in HTML format, I can get it by not using the -B\n"
4959" (enforce ASCII) flag.\n"
4960"\n"
4961, stdout);
4962 fputs(
4963" You also can use authentication when accessing LDAP catalog:\n"
4964"\n"
4965" curl -u user:passwd \"ldap://ldap.frontec.se/o=frontec??sub?mail=*\"\n"
4966" curl \"ldap://user:passwd@ldap.frontec.se/o=frontec??sub?mail=*\"\n"
4967"\n"
4968" By default, if user and password provided, OpenLDAP/WinLDAP will use basic\n"
4969" authentication. On Windows you can control this behavior by providing \n"
4970" one of --basic, --ntlm or --digest option in curl command line\n"
4971"\n"
4972, stdout);
4973 fputs(
4974" curl --ntlm \"ldap://user:passwd@ldap.frontec.se/o=frontec??sub?mail=*\"\n"
4975"\n"
4976" On Windows, if no user/password specified, auto-negotiation mechanism will\n"
4977" be used with current logon credentials (SSPI/SPNEGO).\n"
4978"\n"
4979"ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES\n"
4980"\n"
4981" Curl reads and understands the following environment variables:\n"
4982"\n"
4983" http_proxy, HTTPS_PROXY, FTP_PROXY\n"
4984"\n"
4985" They should be set for protocol-specific proxies. General proxy should be\n"
4986" set with\n"
4987"\n"
4988" ALL_PROXY\n"
4989"\n"
4990, stdout);
4991 fputs(
4992" A comma-separated list of host names that shouldn't go through any proxy is\n"
4993" set in (only an asterisk, '*' matches all hosts)\n"
4994"\n"
4995" NO_PROXY\n"
4996"\n"
4997" If the host name matches one of these strings, or the host is within the\n"
4998" domain of one of these strings, transactions with that node will not be\n"
4999" proxied. When a domain is used, it needs to start with a period. A user can\n"
5000" specify that both www.example.com and foo.example.com should not uses a\n"
5001, stdout);
5002 fputs(
5003" proxy by setting NO_PROXY to \".example.com\". By including the full name you\n"
5004" can exclude specific host names, so to make www.example.com not use a proxy\n"
5005" but still have foo.example.com do it, set NO_PROXY to \"www.example.com\"\n"
5006"\n"
5007" The usage of the -x/--proxy flag overrides the environment variables.\n"
5008"\n"
5009"NETRC\n"
5010"\n"
5011" Unix introduced the .netrc concept a long time ago. It is a way for a user\n"
5012" to specify name and password for commonly visited FTP sites in a file so\n"
5013, stdout);
5014 fputs(
5015" that you don't have to type them in each time you visit those sites. You\n"
5016" realize this is a big security risk if someone else gets hold of your\n"
5017" passwords, so therefore most unix programs won't read this file unless it is\n"
5018" only readable by yourself (curl doesn't care though).\n"
5019"\n"
5020" Curl supports .netrc files if told to (using the -n/--netrc and\n"
5021" --netrc-optional options). This is not restricted to just FTP,\n"
5022" so curl can use it for all protocols where authentication is used.\n"
5023"\n"
5024, stdout);
5025 fputs(
5026" A very simple .netrc file could look something like:\n"
5027"\n"
5028" machine curl.haxx.se login iamdaniel password mysecret\n"
5029"\n"
5030"CUSTOM OUTPUT\n"
5031"\n"
5032" To better allow script programmers to get to know about the progress of\n"
5033" curl, the -w/--write-out option was introduced. Using this, you can specify\n"
5034" what information from the previous transfer you want to extract.\n"
5035"\n"
5036" To display the amount of bytes downloaded together with some text and an\n"
5037" ending newline:\n"
5038"\n"
5039, stdout);
5040 fputs(
5041" curl -w 'We downloaded %{size_download} bytes\\n' www.download.com\n"
5042"\n"
5043"KERBEROS FTP TRANSFER\n"
5044"\n"
5045" Curl supports kerberos4 and kerberos5/GSSAPI for FTP transfers. You need\n"
5046" the kerberos package installed and used at curl build time for it to be\n"
5047" available.\n"
5048"\n"
5049" First, get the krb-ticket the normal way, like with the kinit/kauth tool.\n"
5050" Then use curl in way similar to:\n"
5051"\n"
5052" curl --krb private ftp://krb4site.com -u username:fakepwd\n"
5053"\n"
5054, stdout);
5055 fputs(
5056" There's no use for a password on the -u switch, but a blank one will make\n"
5057" curl ask for one and you already entered the real password to kinit/kauth.\n"
5058"\n"
5059"TELNET\n"
5060"\n"
5061" The curl telnet support is basic and very easy to use. Curl passes all data\n"
5062" passed to it on stdin to the remote server. Connect to a remote telnet\n"
5063" server using a command line similar to:\n"
5064"\n"
5065" curl telnet://remote.server.com\n"
5066"\n"
5067" And enter the data to pass to the server on stdin. The result will be sent\n"
5068, stdout);
5069 fputs(
5070" to stdout or to the file you specify with -o.\n"
5071"\n"
5072" You might want the -N/--no-buffer option to switch off the buffered output\n"
5073" for slow connections or similar.\n"
5074"\n"
5075" Pass options to the telnet protocol negotiation, by using the -t option. To\n"
5076" tell the server we use a vt100 terminal, try something like:\n"
5077"\n"
5078" curl -tTTYPE=vt100 telnet://remote.server.com\n"
5079"\n"
5080" Other interesting options for it -t include:\n"
5081"\n"
5082" - XDISPLOC=<X display> Sets the X display location.\n"
5083"\n"
5084, stdout);
5085 fputs(
5086" - NEW_ENV=<var,val> Sets an environment variable.\n"
5087"\n"
5088" NOTE: The telnet protocol does not specify any way to login with a specified\n"
5089" user and password so curl can't do that automatically. To do that, you need\n"
5090" to track when the login prompt is received and send the username and\n"
5091" password accordingly.\n"
5092"\n"
5093"PERSISTENT CONNECTIONS\n"
5094"\n"
5095" Specifying multiple files on a single command line will make curl transfer\n"
5096" all of them, one after the other in the specified order.\n"
5097"\n"
5098, stdout);
5099 fputs(
5100" libcurl will attempt to use persistent connections for the transfers so that\n"
5101" the second transfer to the same host can use the same connection that was\n"
5102" already initiated and was left open in the previous transfer. This greatly\n"
5103" decreases connection time for all but the first transfer and it makes a far\n"
5104" better use of the network.\n"
5105"\n"
5106" Note that curl cannot use persistent connections for transfers that are used\n"
5107" in subsequence curl invokes. Try to stuff as many URLs as possible on the\n"
5108, stdout);
5109 fputs(
5110" same command line if they are using the same host, as that'll make the\n"
5111" transfers faster. If you use an HTTP proxy for file transfers, practically\n"
5112" all transfers will be persistent.\n"
5113"\n"
5114"MULTIPLE TRANSFERS WITH A SINGLE COMMAND LINE\n"
5115"\n"
5116" As is mentioned above, you can download multiple files with one command line\n"
5117" by simply adding more URLs. If you want those to get saved to a local file\n"
5118" instead of just printed to stdout, you need to add one save option for each\n"
5119, stdout);
5120 fputs(
5121" URL you specify. Note that this also goes for the -O option (but not\n"
5122" --remote-name-all).\n"
5123"\n"
5124" For example: get two files and use -O for the first and a custom file\n"
5125" name for the second:\n"
5126"\n"
5127" curl -O http://url.com/file.txt ftp://ftp.com/moo.exe -o moo.jpg\n"
5128"\n"
5129" You can also upload multiple files in a similar fashion:\n"
5130"\n"
5131" curl -T local1 ftp://ftp.com/moo.exe -T local2 ftp://ftp.com/moo2.txt\n"
5132"\n"
5133"IPv6\n"
5134"\n"
5135" curl will connect to a server with IPv6 when a host lookup returns an IPv6\n"
5136, stdout);
5137 fputs(
5138" address and fall back to IPv4 if the connection fails. The --ipv4 and --ipv6\n"
5139" options can specify which address to use when both are available. IPv6\n"
5140" addresses can also be specified directly in URLs using the syntax:\n"
5141"\n"
5142" http://[2001:1890:1112:1::20]/overview.html\n"
5143"\n"
5144" When this style is used, the -g option must be given to stop curl from\n"
5145" interpreting the square brackets as special globbing characters. Link local\n"
5146, stdout);
5147 fputs(
5148" and site local addresses including a scope identifier, such as fe80::1234%1,\n"
5149" may also be used, but the scope portion must be numeric or match an existing\n"
5150" network interface on Linux and the percent character must be URL escaped. The\n"
5151" previous example in an SFTP URL might look like:\n"
5152"\n"
5153" sftp://[fe80::1234%251]/\n"
5154"\n"
5155" IPv6 addresses provided other than in URLs (e.g. to the --proxy, --interface\n"
5156" or --ftp-port options) should not be URL encoded.\n"
5157"\n"
5158"METALINK\n"
5159"\n"
5160, stdout);
5161 fputs(
5162" Curl supports Metalink (both version 3 and 4 (RFC 5854) are supported), a way\n"
5163" to list multiple URIs and hashes for a file. Curl will make use of the mirrors\n"
5164" listed within for failover if there are errors (such as the file or server not\n"
5165" being available). It will also verify the hash of the file after the download\n"
5166" completes. The Metalink file itself is downloaded and processed in memory and\n"
5167" not stored in the local file system.\n"
5168"\n"
5169" Example to use a remote Metalink file:\n"
5170"\n"
5171, stdout);

5173" curl --metalink http://www.example.com/example.metalink\n"
5174"\n"
5175" To use a Metalink file in the local file system, use FILE protocol (file://):\n"
5176"\n"
5177" curl --metalink file://example.metalink\n"
5178"\n"
5179" Please note that if FILE protocol is disabled, there is no way to use a local\n"
5180" Metalink file at the time of this writing. Also note that if --metalink and\n"
5181" --include are used together, --include will be ignored. This is because including\n"
5182, stdout);
5183 fputs(

10006/* Decompress and send to stdout a gzip-compressed buffer */
10007void hugehelp(void)
10008{
10009 unsigned char* buf;
10010 int status,headerlen;
10011 z_stream z;
10012
10013 /* Make sure no gzip options are set */
10014 if (hugehelpgz[3] & 0xfe)
10015 return;
10016
10017 headerlen = 10;
10018 memset(&z, 0, sizeof(z_stream));
10019 z.zalloc = (alloc_func)zalloc_func;
10020 z.zfree = (free_func)zfree_func;
10021 z.avail_in = (unsigned int)(sizeof(hugehelpgz) - headerlen);
10022 z.next_in = (unsigned char *)hugehelpgz + headerlen;
10023
10024 if (inflateInit2(&z, -MAX_WBITS) != Z_OK)
10025 return;
10026
10027 buf = malloc(BUF_SIZE);
10028 if (buf) {
10029 while(1) {
10030 z.avail_out = BUF_SIZE;
10031 z.next_out = buf;
10032 status = inflate(&z, Z_SYNC_FLUSH);
10033 if (status == Z_OK || status == Z_STREAM_END) {
10034 fwrite(buf, BUF_SIZE - z.avail_out, 1, stdout);
10035 if (status == Z_STREAM_END)
10036 break;
10037 }
10038 else
10039 break; /* Error */
10040 }
10041 free(buf);
10042 }
10043 inflateEnd(&z);
10044}
